rComments: You MUST read the textbook to do well on the midterms and final exam. Her lectures only provide foundational/basic knowledge of what youre going to be tested on and her lectures can be pretty dry. Overall, shes nice, helpful, and happy to accommodate to students schedule if needed.

One of the worst profs I have ever experienced in university. She was not knowledgeable/organized/caring whatsoever. Tests had random things we had never learned before on them. She showed up late all the time (even to a midterm). Expected us to learn hundreds of drug names even though she couldn't even pronounce them. Avoid at all costs.

Extremely pleasant professor and is approachable and happy to help accommodate students when they need it. DO NOT leave reading material to the last second or you won't pass. I found that the exams were difficult in terms of the short answer-- and were marked maybe a bit harshly. Apart from that, as long as you're prepared, you'll do fine.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Lots of homework', 'Tough grader']

rComments: Honestly she was a nice lady and fine, I even had an assignment late and she let me submit it  but something about her personality bothered me and made me hate her

Easily the worst Psychology/Stats professor at UOttawa. Avoid!! She claims she loves statistics but has an awful way of showing it. Lectures are dry and always rushed, each lecture has about 100 slides and spends maybe 45 seconds on each slide. She doesnt collaborate well with the TA. She's a part time prof that will never get a FT contract.

Very bad class. As a person she is sweet and very nice but as a prof she is horrible. Doesn't explain material well and her slides are jumbled and confusing. Exams unbelievably long and unfair. Ended up being just a really bad class. Avoid.

She's a better statistics professor than behaviour neuroscience for sure. Her midterms are lengthy so you need to know all information and be great at writing fast. The assignments are more fair. I would say that if you have to take statistics with her it's not horrible, but if you can take it with someone else, I would.

Well she left with a month left of classes due to pregnancy. Nice person, not the best professor though - "you can read the textbook". Midterm focused on the smallest topics and was worth 40% so pay attention to the details rather than the overall processes. Overall, she's alright I guess.
Awful prof. She gives so much useless information and doesn't focus on the parts that matter. Does not like to be asked questions outside of class. I would not recommend her for any class.

Nice lady - HORRIBLE PROF. Doesn't teach, just reads her slides, lots of "don't need to teach this you guys can read the textbook" and grades are non-negotiable for mid-term etc. Her lecture slides are poorly written and cluttered with irrelevant information. IF YOU CAN TAKE THIS CLASS WITH ANOTHER PROF - FIT THEM INTO YOUR SCHEDULE AND DO IT!!!

Honestly avoid. Teacher makes her midterms and exams so that no students can properly finish on time, and then proceeds to blame her students for "not being prepared enough, it certainly was not my fault". Her slides are confusing and full of mistakes that she just dismisses. She's too full of herself to look at her mistakes and fix them as well.

Really pleasant teacher and very sweet. Invested in her lectures and enjoys her job. Very intelligent despite talking a lot (you'll have to stop her :p). I had the pleasure to sit down and talk with her about psych for a while. Though I'm already familiar with most of the material I tend to crave more details than she provides. Still very pleased.
Makes things 100000 times more confusing than they should be. Adds in a bunch of stuff that we don't need to know and then glazes over the important things.

Professor does not include diagrams in slides which can be a huge problem for neuroscience. Expects the students to know things that are unclear throughout lectures and slides. Exams are ok but a little difficult.
Exams are quite hard but the content is extensive and can at times be confusing so she is not necessarily to blame. Sticks close to the textbook.

Goes the extra mile to give a unique learning experience. Cool labs including classically conditioning slugs, and meeting drug dogs & their trainers! Really interesting course. Get the textbook! It's fantastic and she borrows many questions from its practice tests. Lots of video clips and she initiates great class discussions. Definitely recommend!

Goes the extra mile to give students an experience you wouldn't get in other classes. Prof. Baker brought in various organs for the class to dissect despite it not being a lab class. Has clearly invested a lot of effort in the course as only a few lectures were based of the text. Take this class with her!
Easily one of my top 3 profs this year.

she's super smart. a little inattentive to typos and mathematical errors on her slides/exams, but very clear when you talk to her one on one and reasonable if you have an issue with the way something was marked! quick to respond to emails. definitely recommend for stats.
Was a great class, learned a lot, very easy to talk to, helpful, smart lady.

I really liked her; she was extremely caring and patient with students which helps, especially with an intimidating subject such as statistics. I liked how she explained concepts and how used everyday examples to try to illustrate them. Good prof!
Not the most interesting of teachers, but seems to care a great deal about the subject matter. Material itself is not difficult, but attending class is still useful to grasp the subject matter.
Decent class
Very accessible, attentive to learning needs, subject matter tough but well presented considering. Would recommend.
one of the better ones at u of o

Terrible Prof needs remedial training in basic teaching.  Not prepared, disorganized & confusing & adds uneeded info.  Assignments posted w/o marking scheme & before solved, full of unstated assumptions not covered fully in text or class, huge effort 2 figure out.  Responds that student should be more prepared & familiar vs. fixing problems.

She's a sweetheart but soft-spoken, which was tough for a three-hour 8:30am lecture. Also seems a little distracted - makes a lot of mistakes on the slides and there are typos everywhere. You may have to challenge her on incorrectly marked assignments, etc.. I still did well though.

She really cares about her students. She is new and seems inexperienced at times, but she is always willing to help and has a likeable personality. Tests are based more on the lecture notes than the textbook. Annoying fact: no diagrams in slides EVER because she fears "copyright issues", which is HUGELY problematic for a class like neuroscience
